You need two things: a **navigation guard** in `AppShell` and **`BackButtonBehavior`** on the page.

### 1. Guard navigation in `AppShell.xaml.cs`

Use `OnNavigating` with `GetDeferral()` for the async dialog:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

> **Key:** You *must* call `GetDeferral()` before `await` and `deferral.Complete()` after â€” otherwise the navigation completes before your dialog returns.

### 2. Expose `HasUnsavedChanges` on the page

```csharp
// EditProductPage.xaml.cs
public partial class EditProductPage : ContentPage
{
    public bool HasUnsavedChanges { get; set; }

    void OnFieldChanged(object sender, TextChangedEventArgs e)
    {
        HasUnsavedChanges = true;
    }
}
```

### 3. Custom "Cancel" back button in `EditProductPage.xaml`

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage"
             Title="Edit Product">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

```csharp
// In your ViewModel or code-behind
public ICommand BackCommand { get; }

public EditProductViewModel()
{
    BackCommand = new AsyncRelayCommand(async () =>
    {
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    });
}
```

When the user taps the **"Cancel"** button, it calls `GoToAsync("..")`, which triggers `OnNavigating` with `ShellNavigationSource.Pop` â€” so the same guard dialog appears.

### How the flow works

1. User taps "Cancel" back button â†’ `BackCommand` â†’ `GoToAsync("..")`
2. `OnNavigating` fires, sees `Pop` + `HasUnsavedChanges`
3. Dialog appears: **Discard** completes navigation, **Stay** calls `args.Cancel()`
